default              
defaultFrequent and inappropriate out of area placements increase a young person’s risk of offending and vulnerability; as highlighted by 
defaultthe high profile reports from the Office of the Children’s Commissioner (OCC) 
defaulton 
defaultchild sexual exploitation in 
defaultgangs and groups
default and the Joint All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG) Inquiry on
default children who go missing from care. These reports 
defaultoutline
default particular concerns about the care of children who were placed, often at short notice, in children’s homes a long way fr
defaultom the authorities responsible for their care. Children in such circumstances were vulnerable to going missing from their placements and could be targeted for exploitation. 
default20.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultDfE
default has been proactive in tackling this issue, and recently two key consul
defaulttations were launched 
defaultwhich consider proposals to amend the Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England
default) Regulations 2010. The
default propos
defaulted
default amendments 
defaultare designed 
defaultto ensure that where looked after children are placed out of authority in distant placemen
defaultts they are effectively safeguarded and their welfare is promoted. 
defaultThe YJB has completed a response to the consultation, and welcomes the proposals. 
defaultThe second consultation proposes to amend the Children’s Homes Regulations 2001 (as amended) (“the Children
default’s Homes Regulations”), with a related amendment to the Care Standards Act 2000 (Registration) (England) Regulations 2010 (“the Registration Regulations”), and a minor amendment to the Fostering Services (England) Regulations 2011 (covered at paragraph 12)
default (“the Fostering Services Regulations”). 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe amendments are necessary to improve collaboration and partnership between children’s homes and services in their local communities so that there are effective safeguards in place for the vulnerable group of chi
defaultldren relying on residential care.
default The YJB welcomes the proposed changes.
