defaultSdefaultupport for defaultcareleaversdefault28
default.
default              
defaultThe complex l
defaultegislative rules concerning which young people hit the criteria as a ‘
defaultcareleaver
default’ in the 
defaultThe
default Care Leavers (England) Regulations 2010, mean that many professionals do not understand which young people are entitled to support. It is therefore no surprise tha
defaultt many young people do not understand their own entitlements. The current rules result in a large group of young people who have previously been ‘looked after’, but are not entitled to support as a ‘
defaultcareleaver
default’. This is concerning, and the YJB would recomm
defaultend an urgent review into the current legislative framework.
default29
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultDfE
default also proposes to 
defaultamend Part 7 
defaultof the Care Planning, Placement and Case Review (England) Regulations 2010, in regard to 16 and 17 year old looked after children, so that a decision to 
defaultcease looking after this group of children is not put into effect until it has been approved and signed off by the Director of Children’s Services. 
defaultThis will ensure that there is an appropriate pathway plan in place before a young person ceases to be looke
defaultd after. This is an encouraging step in the right direction, but we would recommend wholesale changes to the current legislative framework are required if the state is exercise its duty as a corporate parent and ensure that this vulnerable group of young p
defaulteople make a successful transition to adulthood.
default&#xa0;
default30
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultCareleavers
default Association have completed some work to address the disproportionate numbers of care leavers in the criminal justice system. They have established a peer mentoring scheme at a number of 
defaultadult prisons, which is showing early signs of success. Former 
defaultcareleavers
default work with their peers in custody, and help them resettle and seek the appropriate support upon release. The YJB are currently in discussions with the 
defaultCareleavers
default Association about t
defaulthe potential to adapt the scheme for the under 18 Secure Estate.
default&#xa0;
default31
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultCareleavers
default Foundation recently received funding from 
defaultDfE
default to provide support to 9 local authorities to better address the needs of 
defaultcareleavers
default over the coming 12 months. The YJB are 
defaultin close contact with the 
defaultCareleavers
default Foundation to ensure that the local youth offending teams are involved in this project, and also to identify any lessons learnt and good practice which could then be disseminated amongst all other YOTs. The 
defaultCareleavers
default Foundation have created a 
defaultCareleavers
default Charter, which they would like all local authorities to sign up to. The YJB will promote the charter amongst YOTs so that they can discuss signing up to it at a local level.
default&#xa0;
default32
default.
default      
defaultA key concern highlighted by part
defaultners is that when a young person moves from YOT Supervision to Probation Supervision upon turning 18, much of the key information surrounding their care status, and support is lost. This leaves 
defaultcareleavers
default particularly vulnerable. The YJB have undertaken s
defaultignificant work in this area, and in partnership with NOMS, recently announced a number of measures and resources to tackle this issue. Guidance for young people on community orders who move to probation has been developed. A similar set of guidance has al
defaultso been developed for when young people move from the under 18 estate to the adult YOI estate. In addition a secure web-based portal, ‘Y2A’, has been created to allow for the safe transfer of all information on a young person to the adult estate. These are
default important and significant steps forward in ensuring that the transition from child to adult support for 
defaultcareleavers
default is more effective.
default&#xa0;
defaultImpact of LASPOAdefault33
default.
default              
defaultThe Committee will be aware that following the implementation of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Pu
defaultnishment of Offenders Act 2012 LASPOA, from April 2013, all remanded young people receive LAC status. Early indications from the Secure Estate are that this has led to increases in the proportion of LAC young people within custody, and then attracting leav
defaulting care support upon release. 
defaultIt is therefore important that any
default Government response considers the impact that LASPOA is having on an already stretched youth justice system.
